<sentence id="0">Human T-cell leukemia virus type 1 Tax induction of NF-kappaB involves activation of the IkappaB kinase alpha ( IKKalpha ) and IKKbeta cellular kinases .</sentence>
<sentence id="1">Tax corresponds to a 40-kDa transforming protein from the pathogenic retrovirus human T-cell leukemia virus type 1 ( HTLV-1 ) that activates nuclear expression of the NF-kappaB/Rel family of transcription factors by an <scope type="spec" id="0"> <cue type="spec" id="0">unknown</cue> mechanism</scope> .</sentence>
<sentence id="2">Tax expression promotes N-terminal phosphorylation and degradation of IkappaB alpha , a principal cytoplasmic inhibitor of NF-kappaB .</sentence>
<sentence id="3">Our studies now demonstrate that HTLV-1 Tax activates the recently identified cellular kinases IkappaB kinase alpha ( IKKalpha ) and IKKbeta , which normally phosphorylate IkappaB alpha on both of its N-terminal regulatory serines in response to tumor necrosis factor alpha ( TNF-alpha ) and interleukin-1 ( IL-1 ) stimulation .</sentence>
<sentence id="4">In contrast , a mutant of Tax termed M22 , which does <scope type="neg" id="1"><cue type="neg" id="1">not</cue> induce NF-kappaB</scope> , <scope type="neg" id="2"><cue type="neg" id="2">fails</cue> to activate either IKKalpha or IKKbeta</scope> .</sentence>
